Graph-Based Resume MatcherA full-stack MERN + Neo4j web application that intelligently matches candidates to jobs by analyzing their resume skills using graph relationships. This project allows candidates to upload resumes and view suitable job openings, and enables recruiters to post jobs and find matching candidates.🎯 Project ObjectiveTo build a web application that moves beyond simple keyword matching for resumes and jobs. By converting skills, experience, and job requirements into a knowledge graph, we can perform more intelligent and context-aware matching, providing better recommendations for both candidates and recruiters.🏗️ Tech StackLayerToolsPurposeFrontendReact.jsBuilding the user interface for candidates and recruiters.BackendNode.js + Express.jsCreating the server and REST APIs.DatabaseNeo4j (Graph DB)Storing and querying relationships between skills, resumes, and jobs.DatabaseMongoDB (Optional)Managing user accounts and authentication.Resume ParsingPython + Gemini APIExtracting structured data (skills, experience) from PDF/DOCX files.API TestingPostmanTo test the backend endpoints before connecting the frontend.✅ Key FeaturesCandidate Portal:User registration and login.Securely upload a resume (.pdf, .docx).View a ranked list of job postings that best match the uploaded resume's skills.Recruiter Portal:User registration and login.Post a new job description with required skills.View a ranked list of candidates whose resumes match the job requirements.Graph-Based Matching:The backend processes resumes and job descriptions to build a knowledge graph in Neo4j.A matching algorithm queries this graph to find the strongest connections based on skill overlap.🧭 Step-by-Step Execution PlanThis project is divided into distinct phases. Both team members should follow these steps to build the full application on their own laptops.Phase 1: Project Initialization & SetupCreate Project Folders: Set up the main directory structure.resume-matcher/
├── backend/      # Node.js + Express server
├── frontend/     # React.js web app
└── parser/       # Python + Gemini API script
Initialize Git: Start version control in the root directory.git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial project structure"
Create a new repository on GitHub and push your initial commit.Setup Neo4j:Install Neo4j Desktop or sign up for a free Neo4j AuraDB cloud instance.Create a new database named resumeMatcherDB.Note down your database URI, username, and password.Phase 2: Resume Parsing (Python Microservice)Setup Python Environment: Inside the parser/ directory, create a virtual environment.cd parser
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate  # macOS/Linux
.\venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1 # Windows
Install Libraries:pip install PyMuPDF google-generativeai python-dotenv
Create the Parser Script: Write a Python script (parser.py) that:Accepts a PDF file path.Uses PyMuPDF to extract the raw text.Sends the text to the Gemini API with a prompt to return a structured JSON object containing name, email, skills, work_experience, etc.This script will be called by your Node.js backend.Phase 3: Backend Development (Express.js)Initialize Node.js Project: Inside the backend/ directory.cd backend
npm init -y
npm install express cors neo4j-driver dotenv multer
Connect to Neo4j: Create a file (db.js) to manage the Neo4j driver connection using the credentials from Phase 1.Create API Endpoints:POST /api/resume/upload:Uses multer to handle file uploads.Calls the Python parser script to get the JSON data.Saves the extracted data to Neo4j by creating (:Candidate), (:Resume), and (:Skill) nodes and [:HAS_SKILL] relationships.POST /api/job/upload:Accepts a JSON payload with job title, description, and required skills.Creates (:Job) and (:Skill) nodes and [:REQUIRES] relationships in Neo4j.GET /api/match/jobs/:candidateId:Takes a candidate ID.Runs a Cypher query to find jobs that share the most skills with the candidate's resume.Returns a ranked list of jobs.GET /api/match/candidates/:jobId:Takes a job ID.Runs a Cypher query to find candidates who have the most required skills.Returns a ranked list of candidates.Phase 4: Frontend Development (React)Initialize React App: Inside the frontend/ directory.cd ../frontend
npm install axios react-router-dom
Create Components & Pages:LoginPage.js: A simple login/register form.CandidateDashboard.js: Contains the resume upload form and a component to display matched jobs.RecruiterDashboard.js: Contains the form to post a new job and a component to display matched candidates.MatchList.js: A reusable component to display a list of matches (jobs or candidates) with their match score.Connect to Backend: Use axios to make API calls from your React components to the Express backend endpoints you created in Phase 3.Phase 5: Testing and Final TouchesAPI Testing: Use Postman to test each backend endpoint thoroughly before connecting the frontend.End-to-End Testing:Upload 5-10 sample resumes and post 5-10 sample jobs.Verify that the matching logic returns relevant results.Check that the UI updates correctly.Polish: Clean up the UI, handle loading states, and display errors gracefully.🚀 How to Run the ProjectStart Neo4j: Open Neo4j Desktop and start your resumeMatcherDB database.Start the Backend Server:cd backend
npm start
Start the Frontend App:cd frontend
npm start
Open your browser to http://localhost:3000.